  <h1>How Burn Injury Settlements Are Calculated</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>Burn-injury compensation is built from a six-component damages framework that overlaps significantly with other catastrophic personal injury cases but has two burn-specific features. First, the reconstructive-surgery component is iterative and long-tailed &mdash; severe burn survivors commonly undergo dozens of procedures over 5 to 10 years post-injury, and the life-care plan has to project all of them. Second, most states treat disfigurement as a separate damages category with its own valuation logic, distinct from general pain-and-suffering. This guide walks through the mechanics.</p>

  <h2>The six damages components</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Past medical expenses</strong> &mdash; documented and reasonable costs from injury through trial/settlement.</li>
    <li><strong>Future medical expenses</strong> &mdash; projected reconstructive surgery, scar treatment, therapy, and psychiatric care reduced to present value.</li>
    <li><strong>Lost earnings</strong> &mdash; past lost wages and future lost earning capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Pain and suffering (non-economic damages)</strong> &mdash; compensation for the burn itself and its quality-of-life impact.</li>
    <li><strong>Disfigurement damages</strong> &mdash; in most states, a separate category from general pain-and-suffering.</li>
    <li><strong>Loss of consortium and family damages</strong> &mdash; available to spouse and (in some states) other family members.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Past medical expenses</h2>

  <p>Documented and reasonable medical costs from injury to trial/settlement. For burn cases this typically includes:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Emergency response and transport</strong> &mdash; ambulance or helicopter transfer to a verified burn center, often a substantial cost when the nearest burn center is many miles away.</li>
    <li><strong>Acute burn-center admission</strong> &mdash; ICU-level care for severe burns, escharotomies (pressure-relief incisions in circumferential burns), fasciotomies, surgical debridement, dressing changes (often under anesthesia), nutritional support (severe burns are profoundly catabolic), infection management. Typical costs: $50K&ndash;$200K for moderate burns; $200K&ndash;$2M+ for severe burns.</li>
    <li><strong>Skin grafting procedures</strong> &mdash; split-thickness autografts are the workhorse for full-thickness burns. Each grafting session involves harvesting donor skin from an unburned area (typically thigh) and placing it over prepared wound beds. Cultured epidermal autografts (CEA) and allografts may be used in extensive burns where donor sites are limited.</li>
    <li><strong>Inpatient rehabilitation</strong> &mdash; positioning, splinting, range-of-motion, early scar-management initiation, mobilization. Often runs 2&ndash;8 weeks following acute discharge.</li>
    <li><strong>Outpatient care</strong> &mdash; ongoing wound care, dressing supplies, pressure-garment fittings, occupational and physical therapy, scar massage and stretching protocols.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Past medical expenses are typically claimed at billed amounts (in most states) or paid amounts (in others) depending on the collateral source rule. Burn-center billing is notoriously high; the gap between billed and paid amounts often exceeds 50%.</p>

  <h2>Future medical expenses: the burn life-care plan</h2>

  <p>This is the largest damages component for severe burns. A certified life care planner (CLCP), ideally with burn-specific experience, develops a detailed projection of every reasonable medical and care expense through expected lifespan. Categories typically include:</p>

  <h3>Reconstructive surgery</h3>

  <p>The defining feature of burn life-care planning. Severe burn survivors undergo procedures iteratively over years:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Scar revision</strong> &mdash; surgical reshaping of hypertrophic or contracted scars. $20K&ndash;$50K per procedure; multiple per year for several years post-injury.</li>
    <li><strong>Z-plasty and W-plasty</strong> &mdash; specific techniques to release contractures and reorient scar lines. $15K&ndash;$40K per procedure.</li>
    <li><strong>Contracture release</strong> &mdash; particularly for hand, neck, axillary, and joint burns where scar tissue limits range of motion. Often required multiple times as scars mature.</li>
    <li><strong>Tissue expansion</strong> &mdash; subcutaneous expanders implanted to grow extra skin, used to reconstruct facial and scalp burns. Multi-stage procedure over 3&ndash;6 months.</li>
    <li><strong>Free-flap reconstruction</strong> &mdash; transferring tissue (with its blood supply) from one body region to another. Used for severe burns where local tissue is inadequate. $50K&ndash;$120K per procedure.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>A typical severe-burn life-care plan projects 15&ndash;40+ reconstructive procedures over 5&ndash;10 years following acute discharge, plus periodic touch-ups indefinitely.</p>

  <h3>Hypertrophic scar treatment</h3>

  <p>Non-surgical management of scar evolution, particularly important in the first 12&ndash;24 months:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Intralesional steroid injections (typically every 4&ndash;6 weeks for active hypertrophic scars).</li>
    <li>Fractional laser therapy (CO2 and pulsed-dye lasers) to flatten and depigment raised scars.</li>
    <li>Silicone sheeting and gel.</li>
    <li>Pressure-garment compression (the gold standard, worn 23 hours/day for 12&ndash;24 months in severe cases).</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Cost: $5K&ndash;$20K/year recurring during active scar maturation; tapers to maintenance after 2&ndash;3 years.</p>

  <h3>Pressure garments</h3>

  <p>Custom-fit compression garments, replaced every 2&ndash;3 months as the body changes and the garments lose compression. $3K&ndash;$10K/year during active treatment phase.</p>

  <h3>Therapy</h3>

  <p>Occupational therapy (especially for hand burns), physical therapy, scar massage. Often years of recurring therapy at $50&ndash;$150/session, multiple sessions per week initially, tapering over time.</p>

  <h3>Psychiatric care</h3>

  <p>Treatment for PTSD, depression, body-image disorders, and burn-related anxiety. Burn-survivor literature documents PTSD rates of 25&ndash;45% in moderate-to-severe burns and persistent body-image concerns at higher rates. $5K&ndash;$15K/year ongoing.</p>

  <h3>Skin and wound maintenance</h3>

  <p>Grafted skin is permanently more fragile than original skin. Lifetime needs include aggressive SPF management (grafted skin is at elevated skin-cancer risk), moisturization protocols, and ongoing wound care for small breakdowns. $2K&ndash;$5K/year recurring.</p>

  <p>Present-value future medical care for severe burns (25%+ TBSA, full-thickness involvement, face/hand burns) commonly totals $500K&ndash;$3M+.</p>

  <h2>Lost earnings</h2>

  <p>An economist projects pre-injury earning capacity through expected work-life expectancy, then subtracts residual earning capacity. Burn-specific considerations:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Hand burns</strong> reduce capacity broadly &mdash; manual dexterity is required across trades, food service, healthcare, manufacturing, and many office roles.</li>
    <li><strong>Face burns</strong> reduce capacity in customer-facing roles (sales, hospitality, broadcasting, performance) where appearance is documented to affect job retention and earnings.</li>
    <li><strong>Heat-sensitive scarring</strong> (grafted skin doesn't sweat) limits outdoor and heated-environment work.</li>
    <li><strong>Ongoing surgery schedule</strong> creates years of intermittent disability that conflicts with full-time work.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For a 35-year-old earning $60K/year with severe upper-body and hand burns, lost-earnings present value typically falls in the $600K&ndash;$1.5M range.</p>

  <h2>Pain and suffering</h2>

  <p>Compensation for the burn itself, the protracted treatment course (dressing changes and debridement are notoriously painful, often requiring opioids or sedation), the ongoing reconstructive surgery course, PTSD, and the lifelong impact of disability. Typical multipliers for catastrophic burns range from 3x to 6x economic damages, somewhat higher than the 2x&ndash;5x range typical of other catastrophic injuries because of the prolonged treatment course and documented psychiatric burden.</p>

  <h2>Disfigurement damages</h2>

  <p>Most states treat disfigurement as a separate damages category. Valuation depends on:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Visibility.</strong> Face, neck, and hands command the largest awards. Trunk burns under typical clothing produce smaller awards.</li>
    <li><strong>Severity.</strong> Mature hypertrophic scarring, contractures, depigmentation.</li>
    <li><strong>Age.</strong> Younger claimants face longer lives with the disfigurement; awards scale with remaining life expectancy.</li>
    <li><strong>Occupation and social context.</strong> Claimants in customer-facing or performance occupations argue larger disfigurement impact.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Disfigurement awards in moderate-to-severe burn cases commonly fall $200K&ndash;$2M+.</p>

  <h2>Loss of consortium and family damages</h2>

  <p>Available in most states for the spouse and (in some states) for parents and children. In burn cases, loss of consortium emphasizes intimacy and physical-contact impact, particularly when burns involve genital, perineal, or breast regions. Add $250K&ndash;$2M+ to significant cases.</p>

  <h2>Worked example: defective lithium battery e-cigarette explosion</h2>

  <p>32-year-old, 35% TBSA mostly 2nd-degree (some 3rd-degree on bilateral hands) from a defective lithium-battery e-cigarette explosion in California:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Past medical: $650K</li>
    <li>Future medical (PV; reconstructive surgery, scar treatment, hand therapy, psych): $1.1M</li>
    <li>Lost earnings (PV; tradesman with dexterity-dependent work): $900K</li>
    <li>Pain and suffering (4x multiplier of economic damages): $10.6M nominal claim</li>
    <li>Disfigurement (visible hand scarring, neck involvement): $600K</li>
    <li>Loss of consortium for spouse: $300K</li>
    <li><strong>Total nominal claim: ~$14.2M</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>Settlement constrained by manufacturer's product-liability coverage. With a substantial product-liability policy and a documented design defect, settlement typically resolves in the $3M&ndash;$7M range.</p>

  <h2>Worked example: restaurant scald</h2>

  <p>45-year-old, 8% TBSA 2nd-degree (legs and lower torso) from a hot soup spill at a restaurant when an inexperienced server tipped a bowl, in Florida. Pre-injury income $45K:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Past medical: $80K</li>
    <li>Future medical (PV; scar treatment, occasional revision): $60K</li>
    <li>Lost earnings (PV; 6 months out, then return with restrictions): $40K</li>
    <li>Pain and suffering (3x multiplier): $540K nominal claim</li>
    <li>Disfigurement (modest; partially hidden by clothing): $120K</li>
    <li>Loss of consortium: $80K</li>
    <li><strong>Total nominal claim: ~$920K</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>Settlement constrained by restaurant's liability policy ($1M limit). Typical resolution: $350K&ndash;$600K depending on liability strength and the restaurant's prior incident record.</p>

  <h2>Factors that move recovery up or down</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Liability strength</strong> &mdash; clear liability (documented product defect, OSHA citation, fire-code violation, repeat-offender landlord) commands top dollar.</li>
    <li><strong>Defendant insurance and assets</strong> &mdash; settlement constrained by what defendant can pay; commercial defendants and manufacturers typically have substantial coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Jurisdiction</strong> &mdash; plaintiff-friendly jurisdictions produce higher settlements; some states have caps on certain components.</li>
    <li><strong>Age at injury</strong> &mdash; younger plaintiffs have larger economic damages and larger disfigurement claims.</li>
    <li><strong>Body location</strong> &mdash; face, hands, genitals, and airway carry significant premiums.</li>
    <li><strong>Documented psychiatric sequelae</strong> &mdash; treated PTSD and depression support higher non-economic damages.</li>
    <li><strong>Burn course complications</strong> &mdash; sepsis, multi-organ failure, graft loss, amputation all drive up severity classification and damages.</li>
  </ul>

